having everything at your finger tips with an ergonimic setting will help..also the mouse and keyboard wristpads.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uziktiny.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ziktiny</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 88<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/14/01 2:39:11 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/warpup/graphics/zikpic.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I may not have to quit EQ after all</span><hr size=1> I have been using the internet for years. I have gotten files, done research, etc. It never occurred to me to look for information on carpal tunnel syndrom.<br>
<br>
Anyway, the good news is that it definately is not a problem with carpal tunnel. The symptoms match a different nerve being compressed, one on the inside of my elbow. It seems that the way I have my keyboard set up at work has required me to sit with my arms on a hard desk surface and this has compressed a nerve, causing pain and numbness. I have changed this setup, and I'll see if it helps. Thanks everyone, I would hate to have to quit while I am still having fun.<br>
