<br>
Heck, I can think of how to bind keys together with proper twist time delays without any outside program. Review the readme file in the eq dir (the macro/hotbutton) section. I've played around alot with linked keys...with the rogue bs/evade etc...you have 10 pages worth of 10buttons, I am sure you can make all the combinations you could dream off. Look into it or send me a tell in game and I'll try to get you started. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/uluteynloresong.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Luteyn Loresong</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#E9D756>(6/15/01 1:31:55 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: I may have to quit EQ</span><hr size=1> I know how you feel. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I have always loved the bard class and after getting bored with my Druid it seemed natural for me to start a bard.<br>
<br>
However, after 40 levels, including some serious charm-kiting in OT my hands and fingers really started to cramp up.<br>
<br>
It got so bad that I could hardly type which is not good considering I use a computer all day as well. It eventually caused me to give up Eq for a couple of months.<br>
<br>
After a few weeks my hands got back in shape, thanks mainly to some serious stretching of hands, elbow and shoulders at least twice a day.<br>
<br>
When I came back the pains had gone but I was very wary of playing my bard again so I got my shaman and warrior up to 51 instead.<br>
<br>
A couple of months ago I went back to my bard for a short while and it was some of the best fun I have had in EQ for a long while.<br>
<br>
Sadly, I took it for granted that my hands would be fine again as I had stopped the stretching exercises after the pain had receeded the first time.<br>
<br>
Boy was I wrong. After a week of twisting the pain was back worse than ever. I have now decided that my health is worth more than my bard and even though it has bought me close to quitting again I have now retired him for good.<br>
<br>
The moral is that you can get around the problem. There is a lot of information on the web showing exercises and stretches that do work to cure the pain. However, do not take it for granted that once you have cured it you will not suffer again. <br>
<br>
When you come back to playing your bard make sure that you keep up with the stretches and do not push yourself if you start to get a twinge again. Inform your group that your hands are aching so that they do not expect you to twist during downtime as much. It is amazing what a minutes rest now and again with some stretching of the hands and arms can do to relieve the pain.<br>
<br>
I sincerely hope that you manage to resolve the problem and that you have a long and happy future with your bard. After all they are the coolest class around.<br>
<br>
Lutyen Loresong (retired)<br>
